unittitle_ssm: Marc Kagan Research Collection on the Transit Workers Union
abstract_ssm: Marc Kagan is a union activist and educator who was a member and leader of the Transport Union Workers (TWU) Local 100 from 1984 through 2010. Kagan's union involvement increased during the 1990s, and he joined the New Directions caucus challenging the leadership of the TWU. In 2000, New Directions leader Roger Toussaint was elected union president, and Kagan became his chief of staff. In 2010, Kagan left the union over a dispute concerning the 2002 contract he helped negotiate. This collection documents the general operations of the TWU during the late 1990s and early 2000s, as well as Kagan's personal membership in and relationship with the organization as both a union member and its chief of staff. The majority of materials document the negotiations surrounding the 2002 union contract including grievances and implementation issues, as well as concerns about sick leave, health benefits, safety issues, apprenticeship implementation, and child care support. The files are both paper and electronic, though the bulk of the records are paper.
